	<text xml:lang="en">
		<body>
<div xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><head n="1.">Introduction</head><p>Ion-microprobe analysis has proved a useful technique for the determination of Li tracer-diffusion coefficients in crystals <ref type="bibr" target="#b0">[1]</ref>, glasses <ref type="bibr" target="#b1">[2]</ref> and silicate melts <ref type="bibr" target="#b2">[3]</ref>.</p><p>In a previous study <ref type="bibr" target="#b2">[3]</ref>, the diffusion behaviour of Li in an alkali-basalt melt was described, using data obtained experimentally and by ion microprobe analysis. Here, using the same methods, the effect is examined of significant variations in melt composition. Data were obtained for two melts, one of andesitic and the other of pitchstone composition, enabling data comparison to be made over the compositional range basalt to rhyolite.    technique used, and sample preparation and analytical conditions for ion microprobe analysis, are described by Lowry et al. <ref type="bibr" target="#b2">[3]</ref>. A thin-film technique was used in which 6Li-rich tracer solution was added to the meniscus of a narrow column of a quenched melt, in 1.5-mm I.D. platinum tubes, which had previously been annealed for several days at the experimental temperatures. Experiments were carried out in air, in vertical tube-furnaces; duplicate experiments at any temperature were for periods differing by a factor of between 2 and 6 (see Table <ref type="table" target="#tab_5">2</ref>). Quenched charges were mounted in resin blocks, ground flat and polished. The modified AEI IM-20 ion microprobe at the University of Cambridge was used to obtain a longitudinal point traverse of 6Li:VLi ratios. The method used to linearise the resulting diffusion profiles and hence calculate the diffusion coefficients is described by <ref type="bibr">Lowry et</ref>  </p></div>
<div xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><head n="2.">Methods</head></div>
<div xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><head>Chemical analysis of the andesite and pitchstone are presented in</head></div>
<div xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><head n="3.">Results</head><p>The determined diffusion coefficients are given in Table <ref type="table" target="#tab_5">2</ref>, together with temperature and experiment duration data. The data are plotted in the form of an Arrhenius diagram (Fig. <ref type="figure">1</ref>), together with data for an alkali basalt reported by Lowry et  al. <ref type="bibr" target="#b2">[3]</ref>. On the basis of a least-squares fit, the data for each composition are, within experimental error, in the form of the Arrhenius equation:</p><formula xml:id="formula_0">D = D o exp( -Q/RT).</formula><p>From this equation, values of Q (the activation energy) and D o (the Arrhenius pre-exponent) were obtained (Table <ref type="table" target="#tab_6">3</ref>).</p></div>
<div xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><head n="4.">Discussion</head><p>Earlier work <ref type="bibr" target="#b2">[3]</ref> on the diffusivity of lithium in a basaltic melt has shown that in relation to several other cations (including Na+), Li ÷ diffuses at a very much faster rate (e.g. over one order of magnitude faster than Co 2+ in a basaltic melt) <ref type="bibr" target="#b3">[4]</ref>. The data given here show that Li ÷ maintains a similar diffusivity in more silica-rich melts. This feature is not shared by other cations; Lowry et al. <ref type="bibr" target="#b3">[4]</ref> demonstrated larger isothermal variations over the more restricted compositional range of basaltandesite for several cations. Furthermore, many of these cations show a decrease in diffusivity with an increase in silica content of the melt.</p><p>The apparent insensitivity of Li ÷ diffusion to melt composition is reflected in the similarity of the activation energies for diffusion in the three melt compositions (Table <ref type="table" target="#tab_6">3</ref>), although a trend of decreasing activation energy with increasing silica content of the melt is possible. In comparison with activation energies for other cations <ref type="bibr" target="#b3">[4]</ref>, those for Li ÷ are the lowest recorded and suggest that the small ionic radius (e.g. six-fold coordinated: 0.76 ,~) together with the single charge, are significant parameters in the diffusion properties of this ion.</p><p>These observations should help to clarify the effect of ionic radius on diffusivity. For example, the ionic radius of Co 2+ is very similar to that of Li ÷ but the diffusion activation energy of the former is about twice that of the latter in a basaltic 205 melt <ref type="bibr" target="#b3">[4]</ref>. Furthermore, the diffusivity of Co 2+ varies with melt composition <ref type="bibr" target="#b3">[4]</ref>.</p></div><figure xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="table" xml:id="tab_0"><head>Table</head><label>